@Iwan Morgan (and others of course) here's a quick 15 min vid I made (sorta run-on, but you'll get the point) that covers most of how I use Wavelab day-to-day. To @Eric Martin point though, I do intake QC in RX and final QC listen/dither/whatever in RX as well

https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fo/noc0zlrykgftkhfr7p0bt/AGGoXe3RKa-gUbbztjLFXwE?rlkey=ecuatquh5re4pmdzocavh1feh&dl=0

This is just an in-the-box flow but covers most of the main points (for me). For analog you can either add your external effect to the clip (which annoyingly stops from being able to hear a reference track). How I capture usually though is to put the clip on a feed track (which is a reference track) send that to the delivery track, and record it in. This way you don't have to render in real time when you bounce or if a small edit, say a different fade or whatever, is needed.

Actually i stand slightly corrected;

1. The remaster on Streaming is terrific, I love it and prefer it to the original

2. the vinyl i have is a 2011 reissue, with original artwork and audio from the 1989 vinyl release. SO, new press of the original mixes. Point is, still sounds terrific.
